Bayesian modeling and prediction for movies

Setup

Load required packages and data.

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(statsr)
library(BAS)
library(patchwork)
load("movies.Rdata")

1. Data

The data contains details about 651 movies that were made between 1970 and 2014. There are a large number of variables which are given below.

names(movies)
##  [1] "title"            "title_type"       "genre"            "runtime"         
##  [5] "mpaa_rating"      "studio"           "thtr_rel_year"    "thtr_rel_month"  
##  [9] "thtr_rel_day"     "dvd_rel_year"     "dvd_rel_month"    "dvd_rel_day"     
## [13] "imdb_rating"      "imdb_num_votes"   "critics_rating"   "critics_score"   
## [17] "audience_rating"  "audience_score"   "best_pic_nom"     "best_pic_win"    
## [21] "best_actor_win"   "best_actress_win" "best_dir_win"     "top200_box"      
## [25] "director"         "actor1"           "actor2"           "actor3"          
## [29] "actor4"           "actor5"           "imdb_url"         "rt_url"

The data has been randomly sampled. Therefore, the results are generalizable. The total number of 651 movies is good enough.

There is no random assignment because this is an observational data set. Therefore, No causal relationships can be inferred. Only associations and correlations can be inferred.

2. Data manipulation

In this section, a new set of variables will be created.

Variable feature_film designates whether the title_type is “Feature Film” or not.

movies <- movies %>% mutate(feature_film = 
                    ifelse(title_type == "Feature Film", "yes", "no"))
movies$feature_film <- as.factor(movies$feature_film)

The new variable drama designates whether the movie’s genre is “drama” or not.

movies <- movies %>% mutate(drama =
                    ifelse(genre == "Drama", "yes", "no"))

movies$drama <- as.factor(movies$drama)

The new variable mpaa_rating_R based on mpaa_rating signifies whether the movies is “R” rated or not.

movies <- movies %>% mutate(mpaa_rating_R =
                              ifelse(mpaa_rating == "R", "yes", "no"))

movies$mpaa_rating_R <- as.factor(movies$mpaa_rating_R)

The variables oscar_season and summer_season are based on the variable thtr_rel_month.

movies <- movies %>% mutate(oscar_season =
                            ifelse(thtr_rel_month == 12 | thtr_rel_month == 11 | 
                                   thtr_rel_month == 10, "yes", "no"))

movies$oscar_season <- as.factor(movies$oscar_season)

movies <- movies %>% mutate(summer_season =
                            ifelse(thtr_rel_month == 5 | thtr_rel_month == 6 |
                                   thtr_rel_month == 7 | thtr_rel_month == 8,
                                   "yes", "no"))

movies$summer_season <- as.factor(movies$summer_season)

Let us remove all “NA” values before proceeding.

movies <- na.omit(movies)

3. Exploratory data analysis

The aim of this project is to create a Bayesian regression model for predicting audience_score from the provided and above created variables. Therefore, in this section, relationships between some of the variables and the audience_score will be assessed.

3.1 Plots of possible relationships

Let us look at the association between the audience_score and the critics_score.

ggplot(data = movies, aes(x = critics_score, y = audience_score)) +
  geom_jitter() + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

The relationship between the two variables appear to be positive and associative.

Now let us look at the audience_score and imdb_rating.

ggplot(data = movies, aes(x = imdb_rating, y = audience_score)) +
  geom_jitter() + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

This too appears to be a strong predictor of the audience_score. The data points appear to be clumped up closely around the regression line.

The relationship between the audience_score and the runtime is as follows.

ggplot(data = movies, aes(x = runtime, y = audience_score)) +
  geom_jitter() + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

runtime appears to be a weak predictor. Almost all of the points are roughly between 75 and 150.

The relationship between genre and audience_score is given below.

ggplot(data = movies, aes(x = genre, y = audience_score)) +
  geom_boxplot() + coord_flip()

audience_score appears to be dependent on the genre variable. This is because the median audience score changes with respect to the genre. Also, there appears to be some outliers in some genres.

The following boxplot depicts the association between oscar_season and audience_score.

a <- ggplot(data = movies) + geom_boxplot(aes(x = oscar_season, y = audience_score))
b <- ggplot(data = movies) + geom_boxplot(aes(x = summer_season, y = audience_score))

# Need patchwork package for this.
a + b

It appears that movies released in the Oscar season have higher median audience scores compared to the rest. In contrast, movies released in the summer season have lower median audience scores.

4. Modeling

Modeling is carried out by Bayesian Model Averaging (BMA) using a chosen set of variables via bas.lm function. The prior is Zellner-Siow Cauchy prior and equal prior probabilities will be assigned to all models. The method would be MCMC because this model has a higher number of variables (16) and this would be difficult to enumerate. The list of variables is: feature_film, drama, runtime, mpaa_rating_R, thtr_rel_year, oscar_season, summer_season, imdb_rating, imdb_num_votes, critics_score, best_pic_nom, best_pic_win, best_actor_win, best_actress_win, best_dir_win, top200_box.

Let us create the ensemble of models.

mov_model <- bas.lm(audience_score ~ drama + runtime + mpaa_rating_R + 
                    thtr_rel_year + oscar_season + summer_season + imdb_rating +
                    imdb_num_votes + critics_score + best_pic_nom + best_pic_win + 
                    best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_dir_win + top200_box,
                    data = movies, prior = "ZS-null", modelprior = uniform(),
                    method = "MCMC")

4.1 Model diagnostics

The following plot depicts the posterior inclusion probabilities for predictors using relative Monte Carlo frequencies of the sampled models (y axis) vs. the re-normalized marginal likelihoods multiplied by the priors (x axis) of discovered unique MCMC samples.

diagnostics(mov_model, type = "pip")

As the two sets are in agreement, we can conclude that we have carried out MCMC process correctly.

The plot below depicts residuals vs. fitted values. The fitted values have been obtained from Bayesian Model Averaging.

# 'par' sets graphics parameters in 'base'. 'mar' is margins (bottom, left, top, right)
par(mar = c(5, 4, 2, 2))

# ' sub.caption = "" ' removes the annoying line of text below x axis.
plot(mov_model, which = 1, add.smooth = F, sub.caption = "")

There appear to be some outliers. The variability seems to be uniform in the middle section of the x axis, but shows non-uniformity in the either ends.

The following plot illustrates the cumulative probabilities of the models for each selected MCMC model.

par(mar = c(5, 4, 2, 2))
plot(mov_model, which = 2, add.smooth = F, sub.caption = "")

It is clear that we have reached the maximum cumulative probability of 1 by using approximately 2000 MCMC models.

Following figure shows the log of marginal likelihood vs. the size of the model.

par(mar = c(5, 4, 2, 2))
plot(mov_model, which = 3, add.smooth = F, sub.caption = "")

Some of the models with highest marginal likelihoods have between 3 to 11 predictors.

The inclusion probabilities of the predictors are given in the following plot. This shows the importance of different parameters. The pink lines show the marginal inclusion probabilities greater than 0.5.

par(mar = c(8, 4, 2, 2))
plot(mov_model, which = 4, add.smooth = F, sub.caption = "")

Intercept has a 100% probability of being included and this is the expected behavior. Other important predictors are runtime, imdb_rating, and critics_score.

The image of the model space is given below.

image(mov_model, rotate = F, plas = 3)

The best model (given by index 1) has runtime, imdb_rating, and critics_score as predictors. These three variables seem like the most frequently present predictors in the top 20 models.

## top200_boxyes         9.715e-02   7.510e-01   5.325e-02

The coefficient of imdb_rating has a marginal posterior probability of not being 0 of 1.000. This means that this variable is the strongest predictor of audience_score.

Let us plot the coefficients of strong predictors. These plots are the posterior distributions of the coefficients of the variables.

par(mar = c(2,2,3,2))
plot(mov_coefs, subset = c(3, 8, 10), ask = F)

The probability of runtime being 0 is around 50%, whereas that of imdb_rating is nearly zero. For critics_score, this probability is about 10%. The range of values for the posterior probability of imdb_rating is far from zero, indicating that this is a very strong predictor of audience_score.

Let us look at some weak predictors now.

par(mar = c(2,2,3,2))
plot(mov_coefs, subset = c(6, 7, 16), ask = F)

All three of these variables have posterior probabilities of being 0 above 80%. Furthermore, the range of their spread contains 0. Therefore, they are weak predictors.

4.2.1 Intrepretation

We can interpret the model coefficient by using the posterior mean of the coefficient which would be used for predictions. This interpretation would be similar to the interpretation of the model coefficient in ordinary linear regression (OLS).

For example, the coefficient of imdb_rating is 14.89. This means, all else being held constant, for each point of imdb_rating, the model would predict the audience_score to increase by 14.89.

Similar interpretations can be provided for other predictor’s coefficients.

5. Prediction

As our aim is to provide a good prediction about a chosen movie from 2016, we should obtains the Best Predictive Model (BPM) from the Bayesian Model Averaging. Let us do this.

mov_bpm <- predict(mov_model, estimator = "BPM")
mov_bpm$best.vars
## [1] "Intercept"     "runtime"       "imdb_rating"   "critics_score"

It is interesting, but not surprising, to see that this model only includes the the best predictive variables as discussed under section 4.2.

The chosen movies from the year 2016 is “Nerve”. The data came from the link: https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/nerve_2016. Let us create a new data frame for this movie.

nerve <- data.frame(mpaa_rating_R = "no", runtime = 96, critics_score = 66, 
                    top200_box = "no", best_pic_nom = "no", best_pic_win = "no",
                    best_actor_win = "no", best_actress_win = "no", best_dir_win = "no",
                    drama = "no", feature_film = "yes", thtr_rel_year = 2016,
                    oscar_season = "no", summer_season = "yes", imdb_rating = 6.5,
                    imdb_num_votes = 120790)

Let us carry out the actual prediction.

nerve_pred <- predict(mov_model, newdata = nerve, estimator = "BPM", se.fit = T)
nerve_pred$fit
## [1] 63.54095
## attr(,"model")
## [1]  0  7  8  9 10 12 14
## attr(,"best")
## [1] 416
## attr(,"estimator")
## [1] "BPM"

The model predicts an audience score of 63.54. The real value is 66.

Let us get the credible interval for this value.

confint(nerve_pred, level = .95)
##          2.5%    97.5%     pred
## [1,] 43.55095 83.53095 63.54095
## attr(,"Probability")
## [1] 0.95
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "confint.bas"

Interpretation: The model predicts that, all else being held constant, the probability of the audience_score of the movie “Nerve” being between 43.57 and 83.50 is 95%. The real values (66) is encapsulated by this interval.

For sake of completion, let us attempt the highest probable model for the prediction.

nerv_pred_hpm <- predict(mov_model, newdata = nerve, estimator = "HPM", se.fit = T)
confint(nerv_pred_hpm)
##          2.5%    97.5%     pred
## [1,] 43.72514 83.63195 63.67855
## attr(,"Probability")
## [1] 0.95
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "confint.bas"

This outcome is not that far from the previous one.

6. Conclusion

In this project, I developed a Bayesian Model Averaging based model for the prediction of the audience_score of movies using some variables. Even though the approach is very different from those learned under OLS (in previous courses), the outcome looks similar. The model appears to be very similar to that of the OLS method.

The model prediction is very close to the real value.

Shortcomings:
One of the limitations of the approach is that most movies belong to different genre. But, the training data contains only one genre for each movie. This can be a problem in real world movie prediction.

Another issue is that the data set might not be fair. This is because most movies are “feature films”. The number of documentaries is very low.

Suggestions:
Use a larger, fairer sample from all the movies created in the Hollywood for developing a better model.
